---
description: Instructions to build and test cudf. Apply whenever you write code and want to build and test changes inside cudf devcontainer
alwaysApply: false
---

## Check if we are in devcontainer

Prompt the user to specify if we are working inside a cudf devcontainer. If not, ignore everything else in this file and don't use any of the following instructions.

If inside devcontainer, ask about the devcontainer environment, `pip` or `conda`? Some users specify this as a part of their `.code-workspace` file name located at `/home/coder` so check that before prompting the user.

Ask at the start of each session if not already apparent from context.


## Building libcudf

Whenever building libcudf from scratch (CMake has not been run before), run:

```bash
export CUDAARCHS=NATIVE ; build-cudf-cpp
```

Note that the `build-cudf-cpp` script is located at `/usr/bin` if you can't find it.

If this is an incremental build, you can just navigate to `${HOME}/cudf/cpp/build/latest` and run:

```bash
ninja
```

Remember, we are in a devcontainer and don't really want to run the `build.sh` script located at `${HOME}` or install anything ourselves. Instead we always want to use `rapids-*`, `build-*` scripts located at `/usr/bin`.

## Building pylibcudf and cudf python
For example, you can build pylibcudf and cudf python as:

```bash
build-cudf-cpp ; build-pylibcudf-python ; build-cudf-python
```

Note that `build-pylibcudf-python` must always successfully run before running `build-cudf-python` or there will be errors

## Clean up
Similar to build instructions, we can use `clean-cudf-cpp` or `clean-cudf-python` etc. scripts located at `/usr/bin`. Use `clean-cudf` to clean everything.

## Build error handling
Oftentimes, clean building cudf will resolve all build problems. If we run into a fatal CMake error while building libcudf indicating packages/version mismatch, we can update our packages using the following script. If the error persists, use `--force` flag with the script

```bash
rapids-make-<ENV>-env
```

where `<ENV>` is either `pip` or `conda` depending on the devcontainer environment. Prompt the user to specify this information if and only if not specified earlier and is needed.

Make sure to run `clean-cudf` after running this for a fresh subsequent build.

## Running Google tests

Run relevant Google tests. Discover all test name binaries at `${HOME}/cudf/cpp/build/latest`

```bash
cd ${HOME}/cudf/cpp/build/latest ; ./gtests/PARQUET_TEST ; ./gtests/HYBRID_SCAN_TEST
```

## Running Pytests

Make sure to build pylibcudf and python before running any of these.

Pylibcudf tests can be discovered at: `${HOME}/cudf/python/pylibcudf/tests` and subfolders. You can use `pytest` to run them. Example:

```bash
cd ${HOME}/cudf/python/pylibcudf/tests/io ; pytest test_parquet.py
```

Similarly, cudf-python tests can be discovered at: `${HOME}/cudf/python/cudf/cudf/tests` and subfolders. These can also be run the same way.
